tweet: Ultimately the risk reward of this approach comes down to the value of decentralization vs the value of stability.

name: Bill Barhydt
tweet: Even with stable collateral, algo stables will always be victims to extreme shocks or black swans that could disable the peg via Counterparty risk even if collateral doesn‚Äôt go to zero.

name: Bill Barhydt
tweet: The cost of the peg in an algo stable should be the cost of shorting the underlying asset. For non volatile assets that cost should be very low and ideally borne by the users somehow.

name: Bill Barhydt
tweet: If the collateral goes to zero the system fails as you need an infinite amount of that collateral to make counterparties whole. That‚Äôs basically what happened with Luna/Terra/UST.

name: Bill Barhydt
tweet: If you wanted to create a synthetic dollar using gold or #Bitcoin or Ethereum that could work (Abra did it) since the collateral is unlikely to go to zero.

tweet: Single biggest issue with algo stablecoins is that synthetic assets based on unproven collateral are a really bad idea.

tweet: If you think a $24B gaming company can't bring down the system you're wrong. Prime brokers can experience huge losses if they're forced to buy back shares on behalf of retail clients if hedge funds fail. That can bring down brokerages and potentially their bank holding companies.
